🚀#ATM Transactions

class ATM:
 def insert_card(self):
 print('Card Inserted')
class Kishore(ATM):
 def transaction(self):
 print('Withdrawing money')
class Pawan(ATM):
 def transaction(self):
 print('Checking balance')
class Nireeksha(ATM):
 def transaction(self):
 print('Changing PIN number')
u1 = Kishore()
u1.insert_card()
u1.transaction()
print('------------------')
u2 = Pawan()
u2.insert_card()
u2.transaction()
print('------------------')
u3 = Nireeksha()
u3.insert_card()
u3.transaction()

#Explanation:
• The parent class ATM provides a common method insert_card().
• Each child class (Kishore, Pawan, Nireeksha) performs a different type of 
transaction.

🚀#Food Delivery Apps

class FoodApp:
 def open(self):
 print('Opening Food App')
class Swiggy(FoodApp): # Single level inheritance
 def order(self):
 print('Food will come late but no coupon')
class Zomato(FoodApp): # Hierarchical inheritance
 def order(self):
 print('Food and delivery charges are high')
class Logesh(Zomato, Swiggy): # Multiple inheritance
def hungry(self):
 print('Orders food from whoever gives free delivery')
obj1 = Logesh()
obj1.hungry()
obj1.order()

#Output:
Orders food from whoever gives free delivery
Food and delivery charges are high
#Explanation:
• FoodApp → Parent
• Swiggy and Zomato → Hierarchical inheritance
• Logesh → uses Multiple Inheritance by inheriting from both.


🚀#School Management Example:

class School:
 def intimation(self):
 print('School Bell Rang')
class Teacher(School):
 def teaching(self):
 print('Explaining OOPs Concepts')
class Student(School):
 def listen(self):
 print('Acting sincere but not really studying')
class ClassLeader(Teacher, Student):
 def manage(self):
 print('Taking attendance and disturbing class')
o1 = ClassLeader()
o1.intimation()
o1.teaching()
o1.listen()
o1.manage()

#Output:
School Bell Rang
Explaining OOPs Concepts
Acting sincere but not really studying
Taking attendance and disturbing class.

#Explanation:
• Teacher and Student are derived from School → Hierarchical Inheritance
• ClassLeader is derived from both Teacher and Student → Multiple Inheritance
Hence, this structure is an example of Hybrid Inheritance.



